To evaluate whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% in order to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring to Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was somewhat discouraging, and it's hard to pinpoint the exact reason for it. With the arrival of winter on a New England campus, there's clearly a decrease in people commuting by bicycle or on foot, which might explain part of the drop. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is busy with schoolwork, grading, and other tasks. Filling out the commuter log might have simply fallen off the radar for many. Additionally, December ushers in the busy holiday season and the subsequent month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus at all. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might also explain the low number of logs for that month. However, none of this really explains the low number of submissions in February. It's also possible that any project of this kind experiences an initial burst of energy and excitement that naturally wanes. To counteract this trend, we initiated the Carpool Challenge Week, a special campaign in March to revitalize the initiative, which resulted in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum in the face of both a natural decline in engagement and the specific problem of holiday and semester breaks in higher education.

Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it's essential to provide incentives for using alternative commuting methods. We distributed many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting, however, to see how larger prizes might have influenced participation—such as offering a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This might have also helped to combat the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn’t really change throughout the project. However, if the value of the prizes had increased over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed more than adequate at the start of the project, but if we had announced the addition of a couple of bicycles in December, and then a hybrid or electric car in January, one can only imagine that participation and engagement would have increased instead of decreased.

While reviewing the Library of Congress’s collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, of which there were fifteen between 1895 and 1901. These films typically utilize creative editing to create illusions. My film study primarily focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier features in some of the later films. Generally, the trick film at the turn of the century is stage-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing elements such as multiple shots.

One of the most notable aspects the trick films share is their filming on an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films and has its roots in the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation inherent in using the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side and do not walk toward or away from the camera. Consider, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even when they exit the frame, the camera does not follow them.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This draws from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at all times, framed by the stage's borders. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.

Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative use of the trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. Note, however, that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer’s eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several joined together to create the illusion of appearance or disappearance. Look closely at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary’s severed “head” begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is essentially an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic style has been criticized, praised, accused of lacking depth, and celebrated for its 'terrible sublime' qualities (Burke). The first "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined elements of both "ancient and modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' natural mimicry in 'modern' novels to present what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily on medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, "gothic" described various peoples, styles, and times, considered archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The combination of theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format (offering a personal view of characters' psychology) has allowed Gothic to persist for so long, becoming both obsolete and new to readers far removed from its original writing.

One of the key gothic ideas in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is both retained and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is crucial for Gothic writers due to what it represented—the classic knight, brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of those ideals in society, particularly noted by writers like Walpole. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (hinting at Gothic's evolution to Romanticism) and is used to seek improvements in the present. Walpole, writing The Castle of Otranto amid political turmoil, despaired over the possible future. Engaged in politics and (arguably) unfair accusations, he might have thought, if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" in people from the gothic era had been lost in 'present' society. This is evident in his writing, particularly with characters like Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, readers can see he embodies many chivalric traits; he is described as:

His depiction includes many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is primarily a prince, he has suffered, been deeply affected by tragedy, left, and is assumed to have been killed by infidels. The "gallant and courteous Knight" image is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the flow of processes that move goods from customer orders through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. He described the entire process of planning, implementing, and controlling activities in the supply chain to efficiently meet customer needs. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these to provide excellent customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process and forms its foundation. It outlines when, why, where, and how everything is produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, which they can gauge by analyzing the market. The market reveals customer demands. Once managers have this understanding, they decide what products to produce and in what quantity. After determining this, they choose where products should be produced, considering which facility best meets volume and quality demands while ensuring customer satisfaction. Once the production location is decided, managers focus on scheduling work and maintaining equipment. Each detail is vital throughout this process; poor planning can cost time and money. For example, my experience at Wal-Mart and Target showed me that having detailed processes allows for smooth operations without confusion about expectations.

The second key element is supply, defined by strategic decisions that determine a facility's core capabilities and guide outsourcing partnerships. A single product may involve many production divisions, each with different equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers decide which division fits best for each process. They might also outsource work to create speed, which is providing quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their emphasis on the aristocracy of the era. Two novels considered Victorian but diverge from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and a penchant for the bizarre, which is atypical for works from the period, thereby strengthening the characters within each story. This provides insights that further explore their motives and emotions.

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas crowded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily arguing, for the very words they spoke echoed in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, ... he found that he was talking to them... Suddenly, he recoiled at the report of firearms; loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult as some unseen hand hurriedly bore him away. Through all these rapid visions ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which wearied and tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels often use this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and function vary in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange events often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, what pains him, and his awareness of the true nature of the things happening around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver vividly relives the shooting as if in a dream while he struggles to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events, as well as the dire state his health had reached, clearly shown through Oliver's hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, all his senses are numbed as he does not notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he experiences his despair anew, detached from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will led to his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, as he cannot bring himself to even attempt to influence the outcome of an event, even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied by this passage, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, influencing his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of his own life.

"The day passed off—day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came—and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary school students. I did my best to help them in whatever subjects they were struggling with, but my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to help a little boy named Adrian (I think he was in third or fourth grade) who was having a lot of trouble reading. It occurred to me that something was wrong; he had the strangest problems. Some letters he knew how to pronounce perfectly, while others he didn't even come close, it was the oddest thing. You know, he was of Latino descent, of that I was sure, but the boy spoke perfect English. We struggled on until the day I met his mother. I was helping to babysit (for lack of a better term) a few kids while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother walked in. His mother didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very limited Spanish (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. But then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read well, he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if that realization helped him much, but I do hope he's doing better now.

I tell this story to address the issue of the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. I also tell it to prove that it's not always as obvious as we might think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can be a huge hurdle. I think everyone can agree that this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was quite simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no single answer. The dual language system, language immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, none of these things alone will solve this problem. The key lies in combining all of these approaches!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." A lot of fear surrounds this idea, that it's a waste of resources, and that the majority of children in schools will gain no benefit. But that's false. If we were to apply these sorts of programs in the classroom as the rule, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from it. How do we go about this though? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No. That would be unreasonable and somewhat unrealistic. However, I do think there is no reason why we can't have special aids, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From childhood, most of us are told that there is something out there larger than we are, beyond our comprehension. Some attend Sunday school to learn about it, others go to temple, or look within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions our parents pass on to us. However, some of us completely reject them, denying that there can be anything beyond our own personal egocentric universe. We might embrace one set of values only to later change our minds and adopt another. Whatever path we choose, we seek to define a part of ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from shadows into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch of our house, listening to the rain pounding on the tin roof above us as we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters directed the rain, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, with a look that seemed half searching, half remembering. He had become thinner over the past months, his clothes hanging loosely on his body. His hair had thinned, sparser than I remembered. He continued to stare into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, frightened, unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because discussing it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a bit closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain of the June twilight.

My father died in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had not eased my father's suffering, but extended his life a few more months beyond the doctors' estimates; I couldn't define what value there was in him simply suffering longer. What kind of God would allow this, I thought. Alone at night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I hadn’t wanted to see him pass from this life to another. So I didn’t. I couldn’t watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember my father for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family, and knew Dad wouldn’t want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of republicanism. Although primarily an agriculturist, his profession, alongside his brief political career, made him known for his dedication and outspokenness on matters of personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system was the foundation for nearly all his opinions on government. His attempts to preserve and promote what he considered the most superior of all careers shaped his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition to hinder the founders of the government, allowing for the establishment of self-governance. He firmly believed in the natural rights of man and that they are interdependent—meaning that if one is denied, they all fail, and the value of the remaining ones is diminished. Therefore, these rights should be beyond the reach of government. He argued that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical prowess and malicious intelligence were the ones who profited, but in civilization, this must not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be established that accounts for the inherent good and evil within man. Taylor was very strict in his views on a dualistic morality. He claimed that "since government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, enhance agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function justly, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by greed and self-interest. He believed self-interest was man's motivation in all things, but this trait was only considered evil when it led beyond creating a society based on the public good to sub-societies that lived at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to restrain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be under careful observation to avoid the addition of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited federal government, with no more rights or powers granted than those explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive federal government was costly and therefore likely despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I stared downward, my mind blankly taking in the view before me. Unemotionally and silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object to any abstract understanding, my mind analyzed the picture in front of my eyes. Thoughts slipped in and out of my mind almost faster than they appeared. My consciousness worked so smoothly and cleanly that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I was observing.  
Once, on the advice of an artist I worked with, I bought an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had wanted to learn how to draw since I was six years old, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to the processes the brain uses to interpret lines. One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study. This transforms an overwhelmingly detailed picture, such as a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit on a simple plane.  
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally project that artist's frame. I was so overwhelmed, so awestruck that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of presenting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic, then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips touched my chosen tool of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind's will taking shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried to nothingness. Muscles tightened, jerked, and spasmed a little more quickly and anxiously the second time, my hand slapped the handle of the toilet again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet.  
Mop loosely gripped in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie uncomfortably knotted around my neck, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are losing their lives in car accidents. Various factors contribute to this deadly statistical trend for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health point out that one part of the issue is that the teenage brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Inexperience is also at the core of the problem. This lack of experience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and running off the road.  
Teens perform significantly worse when traveling with peers—a fact that anyone with common sense knows occurs regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that revealed a correlation between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents.  
California and other states have tried to improve teen driver safety by requiring provisional licenses that limit the hours teens can drive and forbid other minors as passengers.  
However, in my view, provisional licenses are merely temporary solutions. The real issue is that the youngest drivers, as a group, are simply not equipped to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities, according to all statistical indicators. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman argues that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests that individuals under the age of 19-20 have a common drive to take risks for the thrill of it. Therefore, it seems logical to delay driving until the tendency to seek thrills starts to stabilize. If we continue issuing licenses to young teens, we will not only keep witnessing deadly accidents but may see a staggering increase in fatalities in the coming years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, leading to millions of new teen drivers on the road.  
Legislation addressing this issue would be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver’s education classes to initiate the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 should be allowed to operate a vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full driver’s license, with a certain number of practical driving hours required. The specific number of required hours could be based on what most states already mandate (for example, California currently requires 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Since the alarming statistics for teen drivers are consistent across states, uniform national legislation would be a sensible—and in my opinion, effective—way to protect teens nationwide.  
The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This article addresses three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Then, the diagnosis is explained, along with common characteristics or "red flags". Finally, the article concludes with ways a teacher in a mainstream classroom can assist a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), "refers to the efficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activity underlying that processing, leading to electrophysiological auditory potentials" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) cannot properly process what is heard. People with CAPD have normal hearing and are not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the brain area that translates what we hear, separating words or distinguishing conversation from background noise, does not function as it typically should.

The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, referred to as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were studying children with communication disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura introduced "dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 stimulated research on children with CAPD.

CAPD can manifest in various ways: the affected person may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have trouble distinguishing between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may not recognize sound patterns; may not differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on voice changes); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not synthesize sound cues (that is, interpret them meaningfully to act upon); and may not determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function", which may be conducted by "audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using various measures that evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This can include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test consistently used with a high rate of diagnostic success, and no known cause for the disorder. Many tests present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to these signals.

In seeking an education in social work, I aim to pursue a career in the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have been abused or neglected, and to support families in need. The values I contribute to the social work field include service, respect, ethical integrity, dedication to improving relationships between individuals, and personal development to remain proficient in my field. These core values are not only crucial to social workers; they hold personal significance for me as well.

I have always wanted to help others, but I wasn't certain about the career path I wanted to follow. Throughout my high school and college years, I observed many individuals avoiding their problems and some using less than ideal coping strategies. Due to the situations I witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career direction, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy nervously sitting on her couch. She explained he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' home. To see if I could help, I drove to his parents' house. There, I privately shared my concerns with the police and mentioned my recent graduation with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents since the law could not intervene for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they appeared nervous and offered excuses to explain their son's "manipulative" behavior in involving outside help for "simple" disputes. After this experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to assist children with "simple" family disputes.

Another value significant to the social work field is social justice. As a society, we claim that individuals are important and mourn those we have lost. Nevertheless, society's concept of the "individual" often adheres to outdated traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. If we as a society mourn lost individuals, then why do we strive to be like "everyone else?" I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limits on myself to conform to others. Throughout high school and college, I stood against social injustice whenever I could: dyeing my hair in unnatural colors, wearing clothes that suited my personality, piercing my ears beyond traditional norms, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and opposing racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

The following paper discusses the biological and sociocultural models concerning the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model emphasizes inherited genetic information and medical aspects of health. Sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia explores these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and better clarify the models. The research explanations and their findings are critically analyzed to highlight their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be classified as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include dyssomnias or parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are associated with an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders may result from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulties in obtaining or maintaining sufficient sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty staying awake, both for at least a month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While dyssomnias focus on falling and staying asleep, parasomnias are sleep disorders linked with behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review focuses on insomnia and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general concerning the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons specifically responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If inhibited from firing, this can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These results suggest that animal models in mice can be generalized to human studies. This indicates that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, it could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and everyday events requiring monotonous tasks and focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, myself included, navigating the campus can be a challenge. During my freshman year, I was housed in an East Halls dorm, which is nearly the furthest point east on campus, apart from the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my dorm in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which is common in State College. An alum, not much older than me, told me that not long ago, East Halls were separated from the rest of the school by large stretches of unused land. Nowadays, that space has been filled with sports fields and major new buildings like the new Creamery and health services, surrounded by apartments. As the campus continues to expand, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution for mobility issues? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, bicycles alone won't solve the problem. Students have to use them, and the campus needs to be designed to accommodate cyclists.

I was speaking to a friend who recently started cycling again after several years. He remarked on why he ever stopped. "Bikes are fantastic," he said, "for a while, it wasn't trendy to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Besides being good for your health, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus, as far from the campus center as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was to buy a bike. I have classes in the Thomas building every day, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Cycling can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. The only problem is, Pollock Road offers the straightest route to Thomas, but it's not always easy to navigate, whether on a bike or not. Walking has its merits too, but I'm too busy for that. Without my bike, walking would be my sole reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas daily would take an extra 30-40 minutes of my day, adding up to over two and a half hours each week. Plus, there's all the other time spent walking to and from other classes and appointments, which is more time than I can afford.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming threat of technology and capitalism, which is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in his novel "Brave New World." The society in the book values community over the individual and conditions its people from the start to seek immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are portrayed as pawns in a larger game, confined to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Through a Marxist lens, one can observe the author's underlying concerns regarding the development of these systems. Common Marxist terms like homogeneity and reification support the idea that Huxley’s novel is a critique of the emerging economy of his time. Capitalism is satirized using the Marxist concept of false consciousness, where ordinary citizens are prevented from understanding their true economic relationships with other classes, being focused on their own gains. This is seen as a result of ideological control over the proletariat and common workers, demonstrated through the conditioning in "Brave New World." The lower classes, like Deltas and Gammas, are depicted as lacking true will; through hypnopaedia, the drive to consume, spend, and indulge is intensified above all else, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the concept of social classes being dominated by another group, is clearly employed here. The lower classes remain unaware of their manipulation, literally 'buying into an ideology that supports this structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes, though aware, do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, besides characters like Bernard, challenge their roles. The interactions among social classes are significant indicators of the perceived oppression by capitalism. Relationships between individuals do not exist in "Brave New World." The novel seems to refuse to differentiate characters—even major ones lack depth. Huxley may be suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism strips humans of free will and expression. Love and emotional extremes do not exist; interactions remain superficial, illustrated by men’s comments on women’s physical appearances (e.g., pneumatic quality) and women’s unreserved remarks about their encounters. Moreover, each class’s complacency with their hierarchical status reflects the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their complete obedience to their role in the community aligns with Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform with their peers.

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated discussion in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever before. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have personally observed the mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I don't think in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Borac Obama, who evidently has a Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet intrigues me because, based on what I know of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his personality. From what I know and have learned in the past, I thought Muhammad forced people to convert to Islam. He would conquer tribes and then force them to adopt Islam. But according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and even humbling himself to others. After which, one by one, people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

There are also some uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied it so that it was more than enough for forty men. This style of writing makes me believe the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet who needed not to prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This type of fallacy is the worst because it downplays the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it seems like they are trying to take credit for the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.

There are also many stories in the biography that suggest part of their agenda is to provide proof of 'witness' or how people 'on their own' converted to Islam. But the problem is that many of the stories are at least from a third-party perspective. In the story, the author illustrates that he heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so, and so on. I didn't like this much because, although their idea was to prove the truth of the stories, I thought it diminished them and made them appear even more suspicious.

I think what bothers me most about this work is their attempt to exalt and elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his life were swiftly put aside in the development of Christian thought that advanced after his time. Looking at this history broadly, we see Christianity gradually moving further from its origins. Today's world seems to reflect a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive trend. While traditional individuals still exist and will resist any thinking beyond what they were taught, this portion of the population may not be influential enough to sway the entirety. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow immensely in the coming years. A yearning will spread to distinguish the doctrines added over time to Christianity from the religion's original intent. This process might take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: a significant reversal in Christian history will occur. A return to its original form will take place. A movement will expand, stripping away layers of doctrine, one by one, as if the clock were moving backward, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity remains, before any other thinkers claimed such ideas. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if living in Jesus' time, following solely his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead. However, with the theological clock moving backward, the wide diversity in Christendom will shift towards more uniformity in belief and practice. Across regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, differences will diminish, and similarities will grow. Human history is full of major reversals. One example is how Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversal in our future will unfold in the Christian religion, undoing history in search of its source and reducing diversity in the process. It's crucial to note that this process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. So what has happened since Jesus' time? Looking far back in history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion when the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit and was divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" reveals how humans, at their core, are naturally greedy and self-centered. They are primarily concerned with their own welfare, striving to make their lives as good as possible, while neglecting those beneath them. "The Jungle" demonstrates this in several ways. The most evident example is the owners and managers of large factories. Their sole aim is to expand their businesses and factories to their utmost potential. They disregard anyone or anything that obstructs their progress or suffers because of it. In Upton Sinclair's work, "The line of buildings stood sharp and black against the sky; here and there, the large chimneys rose up, with smoke streaming away to the world's end." Sinclair aims to illustrate the massive harm this pollution causes. He indicates that the owners have no concern for people or animals that may be harmed. They are indifferent to the thick smoke plumes from the factories or the runoff of animal waste from the thousands of pens in Packingtown. Additionally, the owners and managers did not care about the employees making them wealthy. They would do anything to earn or save an extra dollar. "From top to bottom, the place is a bubbling cauldron of jealousy and hatred; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere, no place where a man counts more than a dollar." They compelled their employees to work dreadful hours and could lay off large numbers of people without notice, compensation, or job search assistance. During the time "The Jungle" is set, there were few, if any, laws or regulations to protect workers' safety or well-being. This allowed managers and owners to act recklessly, forcing employees to speed up production and work under terrible conditions. Although the book does not state it directly, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to endure the dreadful conditions both in the factories and in their surroundings. There were no agencies or organizations providing information or assistance to the workers. Unions existed, but they often did more harm than good by exploiting the poor workers. The workers were treated so poorly and had no escape from the Packingtown system that they were described as slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, perpetually on the brink of starvation and dependent on the whims of men as brutal and unscrupulous as the slave drivers of old; under such circumstances, immorality is as inevitable and widespread as under the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's better poems, according to his own statement. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain that the Greeks saw as the edge of the known world. Although it's certain Virgil did use the term, there is a more contemporary source that deserves some recognition. Poe had a strong interest in German authors. This quote is important as it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. In his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," Karl J. Arndt comments on the similarity between their poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature states that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. In the poetic verse of Faust's second part lies a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. After her death, he begins drinking heavily and weeping from the memory of his lost queen. He then decides his time has come to die, passing his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, perhaps representing a dark counterpart to Poe's personal loss and his reliance on drinking. Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe's use of the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once in "The Pit and the Pendulum" with the phrase "ultma Thule," but he uses it twice in "Dream-Land" as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes Thule's landscape as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and sees a shaded, colorless world. These scenes would be mirrored in Goethe's "The King of Thule" as he has just lost his wife, is lonely, and has lost his desire to rule or live. The entire poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem. Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known, if only because of his respect for Tennyson. Poe expressed this sentiment when asked if he admired Tennyson. Aside from his connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through the numerous reproductions that followed the original publication.

Under California law, a customer injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice about the spill and failed to have it cleaned for half an hour because he was eating dinner. A judge is not likely to immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify a claim for punitive damages, a plaintiff must provide evidence that the defendant's actions were taken with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result from the conduct, and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer could argue that Martin should have been aware of the probable harm of not cleaning up a spill, as several D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months before Palmer's accident; despite this knowledge, he still failed to have the spill cleaned. Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing but still reasonable given the fact that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate measures to ensure the safety of his store. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, that there was an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne that he was on dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded in the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or in the absence of intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when it is committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights, where the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt like she was missing something, a longing that seemed insatiable. It began when she was about 14, just entering her teenage years, and it lingered three years later at 17. By then, she realized she yearned for someone rather than something. Yet, no boys caught her interest. Some were attracted to her, made awkward attempts to win her over, but she felt no appeal. She often puzzled over this strange feeling, trying to fathom what could cause such an unusual situation for a teenage girl. Years of reflection yielded theories, but none substantial enough for her to seriously consider. So she went on with life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was typically peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people, never arguing with each other, and surprisingly, rarely with their daughter. The only disputes arose when she asserted her independence and free spirit. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, yet she countered their calmness with her vibrant and fun personality, making her very likable alongside being a nice person.

However, today was not calm. As she moved from room to room, looking for new inspiration for herself, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's lovely voice. She rushed in, panic rising as she frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's happening?!" She saw her mother on the floor, seemingly in pain, repeatedly saying "Ow" in short breaths. The daughter hurried to her side, placing a hand on her in an attempt to help. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." Her words were hurried and strained, and her daughter could see she was in great pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me how I can help you." Her mother directed her hands, and at that moment, the household hero was grateful for the strength she had gained from her classes. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove away.

A hospital visit brought the smell of disinfectant and illness, mingled with fear. But she wasn't focused on that, as her mind was preoccupied with helping her mother. She quickly carried the injured woman inside and began calling for help from the doctors. A few concerned faces gathered, and someone quickly brought over a rolling bed and laid her mother on it. They took her for immediate attention, leaving her daughter to sit and worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to retrieve a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This research aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as represented by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is linked with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet is a modified form of the Med diet, distinguished by a greater intake of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, while consuming fewer animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is allowed.

Earlier prospective studies documented an inverse link between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial showed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Previous studies did not specifically address stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were subject to validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with around 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified this way. For each FFQ, body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated, and from 1986 onwards, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging the scores from the two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that might obscure results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The study used Cox proportional-hazard modeling to assess the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as shown by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, there were 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from cardiovascular disease (combining fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard above her head, with a disturbing message scribbled on it with a Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, a series of street protests took place, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were called "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprisings, the general public began to take an interest in the protests. Initially, the Burmese government reluctantly allowed the monks to hold peaceful gatherings, but soon the violence escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, and a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for attending a street protest. While the official death toll is listed as 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army a few days before the official report, is quoted as saying, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you've heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities occurring in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to exert complete executive control over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are considered to be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of such actions include events like the June 4, 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the government's authoritarian rule. The death toll in that particular instance varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead, compared to reports from the Chinese Red Cross declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's 'Third Reich,' a period spanning several years and countries where anyone of Jewish descent was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's influence in jazz largely stems from his long career and his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While his piano presence is subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this task, Ellington excelled as a composer by creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual talents of the band members. He crafted a framework for soloists to improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that utilized the unique styles of band members to highlight musical ideas. This approach emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, producing coherent and original sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's mastery of individual players' sounds and their integration into a growing ensemble allowed him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, references Creole Love Call for its use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the restriction of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, a trait evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses:

Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, then transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody and emphasizing several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, with reeds beginning the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice adopts the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington’s use of voice to add a tone color dimension to this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait that pervades his work.

In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing utilizes the vocal qualities of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich, complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) builds on these ideas, as Ellington effectively uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a mainstay in his orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there restrictions or constraints that affect the direction of evolutionary change? Although in 1917 D'Arcy Thompson stated that "even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," the same can be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study explores how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can be used to illuminate the mechanisms involved in the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to determine quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the limits of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is like a tube traveling over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the shell's central column and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is called the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.)

A method for counting whorls is shown below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view, and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures traveling through time and space as the animal accumulates (i.e., builds) its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have remained largely unchanged over the past decade. While the country is on track to achieve several Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, progress in child and maternal health is inadequate to meet the 2015 targets. The reasons for these shortcomings are discussed below, emphasizing the necessity to strengthen the health system rather than solely focusing on program interventions.

Indonesia has seen improvement in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now meeting this standard. However, this still includes traditional workers like midwives, who cannot perform medical interventions in complicated pregnancies (leading to high maternal death rates from hemorrhage). Hence, progress in this indicator is somewhat misleading, and substantial work remains. Moreover, there has been a reduction in the percentage of diarrheal cases among children under five treated by health professionals. Although postnatal care data is incomplete, it is apparent that this is also a concern nationwide.

Cesarean section rates are lower than expected, around 4%. These rates highlight another issue: while urban areas have a 7% rate, rural areas have only 2%, indicating inequitable healthcare coverage across the country. Access is primarily focused in urban centers. There is also a 27% gap in service usage between the poorest and richest sectors, suggesting that the poor struggle more with healthcare access, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering next steps to enhance neonatal and maternal care indicators, the key question is how to effectively address service inadequacies. Should Indonesia develop specific program approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing solely on maternal and child pre and post-pregnancy care? Programmatic approaches addressing these issues are attractive because they target specific sectors with clear objectives and faster results. However, a major drawback is that heavy investment in one area can lead to underfunding others, with resources drawn to better-funded areas (as seen with international HIV/AIDS funding impacting family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs can result in service duplication and lack of coordination, increasing paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded greatly over the last 100 years, making it difficult to definitively list all the genres. Adding to the complexity, most, if not all, genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have given rise to multiple sub-genres and further subdivisions. It can be argued that the heavy metal sub-genre has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in popular music over the past 40 years. It is expressive due to its wide range of emotions, though they often lean towards the darker end of the spectrum. Its diversity became evident shortly after the genre's inception, as people realized its flexibility and started creating their own sub-genres, followed by further subdivisions, a trend that continues today.

Today, the heavy metal movement has reached a point where there are so many niche groups that defining heavy metal precisely is challenging. It has incorporated numerous themes from other genres, but like everything else, it originated somewhere. To truly understand today's metal music, one must first grasp what the metal movement is and why it is more a movement than just a genre.

In many respects, metal is a movement defined by darkness. It is often seen as "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more violence, and more theatricality. Less primitivism and more proficiency; musicians in metal bands are skilled in their instruments, and this is evident in their music. Metal is also—perhaps unsurprisingly—a movement heavily influenced by drugs. The psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s led people to become more experimental, creating wild, otherworldly records, with drugs serving as a scapegoat for their creativity. Metal possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which were quite novel to the music scene, as much popular music lacked these darker emotional elements. Later generations of metal have drawn some of their influences from the dark, visceral qualities prominent in the Romantic Era. Lyrics like the following convey the darkness that is central to the movement: (Byrne)

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" reveal the darker side of the Beatles. They depict ups and downs, supposedly related to drugs. This song is considered by some to be among the first heavy metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also heavy and dark. The Beatles wanted to prove they could be as intense as the Stones, so they included this track on The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists started creating their dreamlike paintings, artist Henri Rousseau was meticulously crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the well-known Post-Impressionist, depicts not only a woman in awe of the wonders of the land she visits in a dream but also Rousseau's personal dreams and ambitions as a painter. From the beginning of his work, he longed for recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art enthusiasts, and realized he faced a challenging internal dilemma to achieve this goal. The Dream reflects Rousseau's lifelong internal struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to be accepted by the critical art world he admired or to embrace his creative independence and uniqueness, carving his own path.

Before one can analyze The Dream from this perspective, one must be somewhat familiar with Rousseau's biography. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who "enjoyed bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal artistic training; instead, he worked until the age of forty as a gabelou, an employee of the municipal toll service, despite being mistakenly nicknamed douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He thus hoped to find refuge in a new life and turned to painting to offer him comfort and a fresh start. Unlike his contemporary colleagues, who sentimentalized and romanticized peasants in painting, he was essentially a folk painter with the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.

Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and started his career at a much older age, but he was also producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Even after working for many years, Rousseau began to receive proper recognition for his art only around the same time that Matisse was establishing a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two were technically competitors in the art scene, but differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their reasons for painting in the first place: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a trite way, while Rousseau wanted to paint a picture so conventional he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have posited a close connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats states in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That is all / You know on earth, and all you need to know." Much of what we learn in life is acquired through education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics attempt to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are largely attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.
	Furthermore, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for instance, may revolve around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not describe why it is good art. When asked about a favorite piece of art or literature, it is common to hear a phrase like, "There's just something about it" preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the properties of a literary work, there is something transcendent that remains. I believe ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. I suggest that it is this 'something', this je ne sais quoi, which is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience them most powerfully on a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They impact us on a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate for other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a strong force, a united country with its own unique mixture of culture, stretching from the shadows of the Alps in Munich all the way to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture can also be felt from Cologne on the Rhine, through the heart of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it is not surprising that the Germany we know today originates from several different sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe known then as the Tungrians, and that they were previously known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the word "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and battled Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under dubious circumstances. He borrowed this term from the Gauls themselves and used it to distinguish those he had conquered (the Gauls) from those he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war..... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles."
